body:
In a match statement where the value is moved, only one of the two branches got a compiler error, despite the fact that both should be an error, 

I tried this code:

```rust
fn conversion(mut input: String) {
    match check_last_char(input) {
        'f' => {
            let arg: String = input.pop().unwrap().to_string();
            let fahren: i32 = input.parse::<i32>().unwrap();
            println!("Temperature: {}", convert_to_celcius(fahren));
        },

        'c' => {
            let arg: String = input.pop().unwrap().to_string();
            let celcius: i32 = input.parse::<i32>().unwrap();
            println!("Temperature: {}", convert_to_fahren(celcius));
        }
}
```

I expected to see this happen: 
Writing this code I expected it to work normally, but of course, I am not handling moving the value, so it should be borrowed.
The compiler should yield an error for both branches.

Instead, this happened:
```rust
  --> src\main.rs:42:31
   |
33 | fn conversion(mut input: String) {
   |               --------- move occurs because `input` has type `String`, which does not implement the `Copy` trait
34 |     match check_last_char(input) {
   |                           ----- value moved here
...
42 |             let arg: String = input.pop().unwrap().to_string();
   |                               ^^^^^^^^^^^ value borrowed here after move
```
The second branch is the one containing line 42, but this should also be an error on line 36, which is identical to line 42
